Robert Martin wrote:

&gt;  &gt; &gt; Yes. Operations that need to be mirrored (opening/closing)
&gt;  &gt; probably don&#39;t
&gt;  &gt; &gt; belong in the constructor since Java doesn&#39;t give us an obvious
&gt;  &gt; &gt; counterpart.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; I think they belong in a template method, myself.
&gt; 
&gt; Or in a Command object:
&gt; 
&gt; interface Command { public void execute();}
&gt; 
&gt; public class FileProcessor {
&gt; public static void process(File f, Command c) {
&gt; f.open();
&gt; c.execute();
&gt; f.close();
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; This is roughly equivalent to the Ruby idiom of using blocks:
&gt; 
&gt; def processfile(f, &proc)
&gt; f.open
&gt; proc.call(f)
&gt; f.close
&gt; end
&gt; 
&gt; Which lets you do:
&gt; processFile(myFile) {|theFile| ...}

Exactly: the Command is essentially an implementation of the primitive 
operations in a Template Method.
